It may be true that the image which gives rise to the intuitive perception of the axiom, is not consciously contemplated as more perfect than the corresponding figure as seen in a body3 but this does not prove that the axiom is really generalized fron] the lattere. The inadequacy of sensible magnitudes for mathematica] certainty does not arise from that of which we are immediately consciens, but from that of which we are not. The straight line as perceived is a quality of body3 the straight line as imagined is a modification of space. The portions of the two actually presented at any time may not apparently differ from each other; but our empirical knowledge or ignorance of body may suggest actual or possible variations not perceived in the in- tuition3 for the qualities of body have an objective existence independently of our perception, and therefore may or may not be adequately perceived at any one time. We see, for example, that a line running along the earth's surface is apparently straight, but we know that it is in reality an arc of the earth’s curvature, and might be seen to be so in another position or with more acute organs. But the straight line in space exists only as imagined, and is imagined only as mathematically exact. The intuition‚ therefore, is adequate and valid for any extent of space, and in any portion.
